# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anecdata-org
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Activism may be performed on a day-to-day basis in a wide variety of ways, including through the creation of art (artivism), computer hacking (hacktivism), or simply in how one chooses to spend their money (economic activism).
[src:anecdata-org/activism] For example, the refusal to buy clothes or other merchandise from a company as a protest against the exploitation of workers by that company could be considered an expression of activism.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] However, the term commonly refers to a form of collective action, in which numerous individuals coordinate an act of protest together.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Collective action that is purposeful, organized, and sustained over a period of time becomes known as a social movement.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Historically, activists have used literature, including pamphlets, tracts, and books to disseminate or propagate their messages and attempt to persuade their readers of the justice of their cause.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Research has now begun to explore how contemporary activist groups use social media to facilitate civic engagement and collective action combining politics with technology.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Left-wing and right-wing online activists often use different tactics.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Hashtag activism and offline protest are more common on the left.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Working strategically with partisan media, migrating to alternative platforms, and manipulation of mainstream media are more common on the right (in the United States).
[src:anecdata-org/activism] In addition, the perception of increased left-wing activism in science and academia may decrease conservative trust in science and motivate some forms of conservative activism, including on college campuses.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Some scholars have also shown how the influence of very wealthy Americans is a form of activism.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Separating activism and terrorism can be difficult and has been described as a 'fine line'.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The *Online Etymology Dictionary* records the English words "activism" and "activist" as in use in the political sense from the year 1920 or 1915 respectively.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The history of the word *activism* traces back to earlier understandings of collective behavior and social action.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] As late as 1969 *activism was* defined as "the policy or practice of doing things with decision and energy", without regard to a political signification, whereas *social action was* defined as "organized action taken by a group to improve social conditions", without regard to normative status.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Following the surge of "new social movements" in the United States during the 1960s, activism came to be understood as a rational and legitimate democratic form of protest or appeal.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] In English history, the Peasants' Revolt erupted in response to the imposition of a poll tax, and has been paralleled by other rebellions and revolutions in Hungary, Russia, and more recently, for example, Hong Kong.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] In 1930 under the leadership of Mahatma Gandhi thousands of protesting Indians participated in the Salt March, as a protest against the oppressive taxes of their government, resulting in the imprisonment of 60,000 people and eventually independence of their nation.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Activism has had major impacts on Western societies as well, particularly over the past century through social movements such as the Labour movement, the women's rights movement, and the civil rights movement.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Activism has often been thought to address either human rights or environmental concerns, but libertarian and religious right activism are also important types.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] In the 21st century, the intersection between human rights and environmentalism has become increasingly important, leading to criticism of the mainstream environmentalist movement and the development of the environmental justice and climate justice movements.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Human rights activism seeks to protect basic rights such as those laid out in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights including such liberties as: right to life, citizenship, and property, freedom of movement; constitutional freedoms of thought, expression, religion, peaceful assembly; and others.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The foundations of the global human rights movement involve resistance to colonialism, imperialism, slavery, racism, segregation, patriarchy, and oppression of indigenous peoples.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Instead, it is between an emergent group (Activists) that fuses *both ideologies* and a less ideological category of 'somewhat conservative' Establishment Republicans." One example of this activism is the Tea Party movement.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Pew Research identified a "group of 'Staunch Conservatives' (11 percent of the electorate) who are strongly religious, across-the-board socially and economically conservative, and more politically active than other groups on the Right.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Activists employ many different methods, or tactics, in pursuit of their goals.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The tactics chosen are significant because they can determine how activists are perceived and what they are capable of accomplishing.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] For example, nonviolent tactics generally tend to garner more public sympathy than violent ones. and are more than twice as effective in achieving stated goals.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Historically, most activism has focused on creating substantive changes in the policy or practice of a government or industry.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Some activists try to persuade people to change their behavior directly (see also direct action), rather than to persuade governments to change laws.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] For example, the cooperative movement seeks to build new institutions which conform to cooperative principles, and generally does not lobby or protest politically.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Other activists try to persuade people or government policy to remain the same, in an effort to counter change.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Greta Thunberg a Swedish climate activist is known for founding the Fridays for Future movement.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Charles Tilly developed the concept of a "repertoire of contention", which describes the full range of tactics available to activists at a given time and place.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] This repertoire consists of all of the tactics which have been proven to be successful by activists in the past, such as boycotts, petitions, marches, and sit-ins, and can be drawn upon by any new activists and social movements.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Activists may also innovate new tactics of protest.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] These may be entirely novel, such as Douglas Schuler's idea of an "activist road trip", or may occur in response to police oppression or countermovement resistance.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] New tactics then spread to others through a social process known as diffusion, and if successful, may become new additions to the activist repertoire.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Activism is not an activity always performed by those who profess activism as a profession.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The term "activist" may apply broadly to anyone who engages in activism, or narrowly limited to those who choose political or social activism as a vocation or characteristic practice.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Helena Alviar Garcia has combined activism with her work as a legal scholar, resulting in academia being seen as activism.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Judges may employ judicial activism to promote their own conception of the social good.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The definition of judicial activism and whether a specific decisions is activist are controversial political issues.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The legal systems of different nations vary in the extent that judicial activism may be permitted.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Activists can also be public watchdogs and whistle blowers by holding government agencies accountable to oversight and transparency.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Political activism may also include political campaigning, lobbying, voting, or petitioning.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Often political activists also publish their ideas themselves via newsletters, periodicals, presses, or digital media.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Political activism does not depend on a specific ideology or national history, as can be seen, for example, in the importance of conservative British women in the 1920s on issues of tariffs.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Political activism, although often identified with young adults, occurs across peoples entire life-courses.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The power of Internet activism came into a global lens with the Arab Spring protests starting in late 2010.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] People living in the Middle East and North African countries that were experiencing revolutions used social networking to communicate information about protests, including videos recorded on smart phones, which put the issues in front of an international audience.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] This was one of the first occasions in which social networking technology was used by citizen-activists to circumvent state-controlled media and communicate directly with the rest of the world.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] These types of practices of Internet activism were later picked up and used by other activists in subsequent mass mobilizations, such as the 15-M Movement in Spain in 2011, Occupy Gezi in Turkey in 2013, and more.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Online "left- and right-wing activists use digital and legacy media differently to achieve political goals".
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Left-wing online activists are usually more involved in traditional "hashtag activism" and offline protest, while right-wing activists may "manipulate legacy media, migrate to alternative platforms, and work strategically with partisan media to spread their messages".
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Research suggests right-wing online activists are more likely to use "strategic disinformation and conspiracy theories".
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Internet activism may also refer to activism which focuses on protecting or changing the Internet itself, also known as digital rights.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The Digital Rights movement consists of activists and organizations, such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation, who work to protect the rights of people in relation to new technologies, particularly concerning the Internet and other information and communications technologies.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Many contemporary activists now utilize new tactics through the Internet and other information and communication technologies (ICTs), also known as Internet activism or cyber-activism.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Some scholars argue that many of these new tactics are digitally analogous to the traditional offline tools of contention.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Other digital tactics may be entire new and unique, such as certain types of hacktivism.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Together they form a new "digital repertoire of contention" alongside the existing offline one.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The rising use of digital tools and platforms by activists has also increasingly led to the creation of decentralized networks of activists that are self-organized and leaderless, or what is known as **franchise activism**.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Economic activism involves using the economic power of government, consumers, and businesses for social and economic policy change.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Both conservative and liberal groups use economic activism as a form of pressure to influence companies and organizations to oppose or support particular political, religious, or social values and behaviors.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] This may be done through ethical consumerism to reinforce "good" behavior and support companies one would like to succeed, or through boycott or divestment to penalize "bad" behavior and pressure companies to change or go out of business.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Brand activism is the type of activism in which business plays a leading role in the processes of social change.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Applying brand activism, businesses show concern for the communities they serve, and their economic, social, and environmental problems, which allows businesses to build sustainable and long-term relationships with the customers and prospects.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Kotler and Sarkar defined the phenomenon as an attempt by firms to solve the global problems its future customers and employees care about.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Consumer activism consists of activism carried out on behalf of consumers for consumer protection or by consumers themselves.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] For instance, activists in the free produce movement of the late 1700s protested against slavery by boycotting goods produced with slave labor.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Today, vegetarianism, veganism, and freeganism are all forms of consumer activism which boycott certain types of products.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Shareholder activism involves shareholders using an equity stake in a corporation to put pressure on its management.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The goals of activist shareholders range from financial (increase of shareholder value through changes in corporate policy, financing structure, cost cutting, etc.) to non-financial (disinvestment from particular countries, adoption of environmentally friendly policies, etc.).
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Design activism locates design at the center of promoting social change, raising awareness on social/political issues, or questioning problems associated with mass production and consumerism.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Design Activism is not limited to one type of design.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Art activism or artivism utilizes the medium of visual art as a method of social or political commentary.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Art activism can activate utopian thinking, which is imagining about an ideal society that is different from the current society, which is found to be effective for increasing collective action intentions.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Fashion activism was coined by Celine Semaan.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Fashion activism is a type of activism that ignites awareness by giving consumers tools to support change, specifically in the fashion industry.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] It has been used as an umbrella term for many social and political movements that have taken place in the industry.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Fashion Activism uses a participatory approach to a political activity.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Craft activism or craftivism is a type of visual activism that allows people to bring awareness to political or social discourse.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] It is a creative approach to activism as it allows people to send short and clear messages to society.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] People who contribute to craftivism are called "craftivists".
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Activism in literature may publish written works that express intended or advocated reforms.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Alternatively, literary activism may also seek to reform perceived corruption or entrenched systems of power within the publishing industry.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Science activism may include efforts to better communicate science or advocate for funding of scientific research.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] It may also include efforts to increase perceived legitimacy of particular scientific fields or respond to the politicization of particular fields.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Some forms of science or scholarly activism on political topics can reduce the separation of science from political advocacy and reduce the credibility of science.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The March for Science held around the world in 2017 and 2018 were notable examples of science activism.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Approaches to science activism vary from protests to more psychological, marketing-oriented approaches that takes into account such factors as individual sense of self, aversion to solutions to problems, and social perceptions.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Some groups and organizations participate in activism to such an extent that it can be considered as an industry.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] In these cases, activism is often done full-time, as part of an organization's core business.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Many organizations in the activism industry are either non-profit organizations or non-governmental organizations with specific aims and objectives in mind.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Most activist organizations do not manufacture goods, but rather mobilize personnel to recruit funds and gain media coverage.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] The term *activism industry* has often been used to refer to outsourced fundraising operations.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] However, activist organizations engage in other activities as well.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Lobbying, or the influencing of decisions made by government, is another activist tactic.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Many groups, including law firms, have designated staff assigned specifically for lobbying purposes.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] In the United States, lobbying is regulated by the federal government.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Many government systems encourage public support of non-profit organizations by granting various forms of tax relief for donations to charitable organizations.
[src:anecdata-org/activism] Governments may attempt to deny these benefits to activists by restricting the political activity of tax-exempt organizations.
[src:anecdata-org/anecdata-org] The Litter-Free Digital Journal is a project from the South Carolina Aquarium hosted on Anecdata.org with a custom app, that encourages participants to track and remove plastics and other litter from both land and water.
[src:anecdata-org/anecdata-org] Users Since the start of the project in 2016, data from more than 7,000 litter cleanups have been entered into the project by more than 1,500 citizen scientists.
[src:anecdata-org/anecdata-org] In 2017, a total of 9,746 pieces of trash were logged and 2,333 total litter pieces in 2018.
[src:anecdata-org/anecdata-org] However, in 2019 the number of litter pieces recorded grew to 32,600 and in 2020, more than doubled, with 74,977 pieces of trash collected and logged.
[src:anecdata-org/anecdata-org] The data from this project has inspired participant activism and has been used to influence public policy in South Carolina, including plastic bag bans.
[src:anecdata-org/anecdata-org] The Great Green Crab Hunt project is a citizen science project led by the University of New Hampshire and the New Hampshire Sea Grant and hosted on Anecdata.org.
[src:anecdata-org/anecdata-org] The project aims to support scientists and policymakers in finding solutions to the problems caused by the invasive species, European green crabs.
[src:anecdata-org/anecdata-org] The project uses a mobile app and participants document the number, shell hardness, sex, and size of crabs seen during one hour.
[src:anecdata-org/anecdata-org] Since the project's inception in 2019, more than 100 observations documenting more than 400 crabs have been added to the project.
[src:anecdata-org/australian-citizen-science-association] The **Australian Citizen Science Association** (ACSA) is a membership-based organisation that promotes public participation in science and research projects in Australia and internationally.
[src:anecdata-org/australian-citizen-science-association] The organisation provides a range of knowledge sharing, networking, professional development, advocacy and promotional opportunities for members and the community to participate in citizen science.
[src:anecdata-org/australian-citizen-science-association] The Association operates nationally as well as through five state-based chapters.
[src:anecdata-org/australian-citizen-science-association] ACSA is an incorporated association registered with the Australian Charities and Not-for-profits Commission in 2018.
[src:anecdata-org/australian-citizen-science-association] The Association supports a range of activities including a national conference held every two years, workshops and training, bioblitz campaigns, a small grants program, public outreach and education, and collaboration with national and international organisations.
[src:anecdata-org/australian-citizen-science-association] The Association has a memorandum of understanding with other citizen science organisations including the US Citizen Science Association, the European Citizen Science Association, Citizen Science Asia and CitSci Africa Association.
[src:anecdata-org/australian-citizen-science-association] The ACSA is a member of the Citizen Science Global Partnership.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Bar Harbor is also home to the largest parts of Acadia National Park, including Cadillac Mountain, the highest point within 25 miles (40 km) of the coastline of the Eastern United States.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] From the mainland, Bar Harbor is accessible by road via Maine State Route 3.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The island is directly accessible by air at Hancock County–Bar Harbor Airport, and by ferry from Winter Harbor, Maine, and Yarmouth, Nova Scotia.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The town of Bar Harbor was founded on the northeast shore of Mount Desert Island, which the Wabanaki Indians knew as *Pemetic*, meaning "range of mountains" or "mountains seen at a distance." The Wabanaki seasonally fish, hunt and gather berries, clams, and other shellfish in the area.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] They speak of Bar Harbor as *Man-es-ayd'ik* ("clam-gathering place") or *Ah-bays'auk* ("clambake place"), leaving great piles of shells as evidence of this abundance.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] In early September 1604, French explorer Samuel de Champlain ran aground on a rock ledge believed to be Egg Rock, just off Otter Cliffs, and when he came ashore to repair his boat he met local natives.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Champlain named the island *Isles des Monts Deserts*, meaning "island of barren mountains"—now called Mount Desert Island, the largest island in Maine.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] In 1761, Abraham Somes established the first European village on Mount Desert Island, naming it Somesville.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Also named for him is Somes Sound, the only naturally occurring fjard on the East Coast of the US.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Bar Harbor itself was incorporated as Eden on February 23, 1796.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Early industries included fishing, lumbering and shipbuilding.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] With the best soil on Mount Desert Island, it also developed agriculture, with a main focus on dairy.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] In the 1840s, its rugged maritime scenery attracted the Hudson River School and Luminism artists Thomas Cole, Frederic Edwin Church, William Hart and Fitz Henry Lane.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Inspired by their paintings, journalists, sportsmen and "rusticators" followed.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Agamont House, the first hotel in Eden, was established in 1855 by Tobias Roberts.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Birch Point, the first summer estate, was built in 1868 for Alpheus Harding.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] By 1880, there were 30 hotels, including the Mira Monte Inn, a historic landmark that survived a massive fire in 1947.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Tourists were arriving by train and ferry to the Gilded Age resort that would rival Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The rich and famous tried to outdo each other with entertaining and estates, often hiring landscape gardener and landscape architect Beatrix Farrand, a resident at local Reef Point Estate, to design their gardens.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] A glimpse of their lifestyles was available from the Shore Path, a coastal path skirting waterfront lawns.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Yachting, garden parties at the Pot & Kettle Club, and carriage rides up Cadillac Mountain were popular diversions.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Others enjoyed horse-racing at Robin Hood Park-Morrell Park.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] US President William Howard Taft played golf in 1910 at the Kebo Valley Golf Club.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] He was the last sitting president to visit the town until Barack Obama in July 2010.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] On March 3, 1918, Eden was renamed Bar Harbor, after the sand bar, visible at low tide, which leads across to Bar Island and forms the rear of the harbor.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The name would become synonymous with elite wealth.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] It was the birthplace of vice-president Nelson Rockefeller.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Bar Harbor was also used for naval practices during World War II.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] More specifically, Bald Porcupine Island (one of the five Porcupine Islands) was used to as a target for live torpedoes.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] In October 1944, the submarine USS *Piper* (SS-409) fired 12 live torpedoes at the island.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Of those fired, one failed to explode on the first attempt but was later detonated by the twelfth torpedo.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Army Corps of Engineers surveyed all 30 acres of Bald Porcupine Island for unexploded ordnance.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Many influential people have called Bar Harbor home for at least part of the year.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Rockefeller of Standard Oil Co., donated about one-third of the land in Acadia National Park and built the carriage roads that are used for hiking and biking.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Morgan owned a house that is adjacent to the town.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Cornelius Vanderbilt built "cottages" in Bar Harbor, while the Astor family owned hotels and cottages in Bar Harbor and the surrounding areas.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Roxanne Quimby, co-founder and CEO of Burt's Bees, has a home near Bar Harbor.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Martha Stewart owns property in nearby Seal Harbor and frequents Bar Harbor.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] In mid-October 1947, Maine experienced a severe drought, seeing only half of its usual rainfall.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] On October 17, sparks at a cranberry bog near Town Hill ignited a wildfire that intensified over the next ten days, due to strong winds that began on October 21, and it was not declared out until mid-November.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] This was one of several wildfires in the state that year.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Nearly half the eastern side of Mount Desert Island burned, including 67 "cottages"—nearly one-third of the 222 cottages that stood at the time.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] (Many were empty or for sale; only 135 were occupied that summer.) Five historic grand hotels were also destroyed.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] These were Agamont House (Main Street), Hamor House (Main Street at Cottage Street), Belmont Hotel (Mount Desert and Kebo Streets), Malvern Hotel (Kebo Street) and the DeGregoire Hotel (Eden Street at West Street).
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The Building of Arts civic building, on Kebo Street at Cromwell Harbor Road, also perished.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Over 10,000 acres (4,000 hectares) of Acadia National Park were destroyed.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The town's business district was spared, including Mount Desert Street, where several former summer homes within a historic district listed on the National Register of Historic Places operate as inns.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] According to the United States Census Bureau, the town has a total area of 63.11 square miles (163.45 km2), of which 42.24 square miles (109.40 km2) is land and 20.87 square miles (54.05 km2) is water.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Bar Harbor is situated on Frenchman Bay, with multiple smaller islands just offshore.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Twice a day, at low tide, a sand bar (Bar Harbor's namesake) is exposed, linking the town to Bar Island.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] This climatic region is typified by large seasonal temperature differences, with warm to hot (and often humid) summers and cold (sometimes severely cold) winters.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] According to the Köppen climate classification system, Bar Harbor has a humid continental climate, abbreviated "Dfb" on climate maps.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Bar Harbor and Mount Desert Island are located near the coastline and surrounded by the North American continent to the northeast and southwest.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] This location, combined with prevailing winds that are not from the Atlantic, gives Bar Harbor a continental climate with very cold winters for an island location at such a low latitude.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] As of the census of 2010, there were 5,235 people, 2,427 households, and 1,275 families residing in the town.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The population density was 123.9 inhabitants per square mile (47.8/km2).
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] There were 3,495 housing units at an average density of 82.7 units per square mile (31.9 units/km2).
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The racial makeup of the town was 94.7% White, 0.8% African American, 0.2% Native American, 2.8% Asian, 0.4% from other races, and 1.2% from two or more races.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 1.1% of the population.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] There were 2,427 households, of which 22.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.8% were married couples living together, 6.8% had a female householder with no husband present, 3.0% had a male householder with no wife present, and 47.5% were non-families.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] 36.0% of all households were made up of individuals, and 14.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The average household size was 2.08 and the average family size was 2.70.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The median age in the town was 45.3 years.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] 17.3% of residents were under the age of 18; 10% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 22.4% were from 25 to 44; 32.3% were from 45 to 64; and 18.1% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The gender makeup of the town was 46.3% male and 53.7% female.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] As of the census of 2000, there were 4,820 people, 2,142 households, and 1,163 families residing in or near the town.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The population density was 114.2 inhabitants per square mile (44.1/km2).
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] There were 2,805 housing units at an average density of 66.5 units per square mile (25.7 units/km2).
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The racial makeup of the town was 97.88% White, 0.15% Black or African American, 0.21% Native American, 0.89% Asian, 0.08% from other races, and 0.79% from two or more races.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 0.62% of the population.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] There were 2,142 households, out of which 24.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 44.5% were married couples living together, 6.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 45.7% were non-families.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] 34.7% of all households were made up of individuals, and 13.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The average household size was 2.16 and the average family size was 2.78.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] In and near the town, the population was spread out, with 19.8% under the age of 18, 9.0% from 18 to 24, 28.6% from 25 to 44, 26.6% from 45 to 64, and 16.1% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] For every 100 females, there were 87.5 males.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 82.7 males.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The median income for a household in or near the town was $37,481, and the median income for a family was $51,989.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Males had a median income of $31,085 versus $25,417 for females.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The per capita income for the area was $24,103.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] About 4.9% of families and 8.9% of the population were below the poverty line, including 6.7% of those under age 18 and 8.3% of those age 65 or over.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] It is in the Bar Harbor School District, an elementary school district, and the Mount Desert Community School District (for secondary school).
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Conners Emerson School, founded in 1962, is located in Bar Harbor, serving students of grades K through 8.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Mount Desert Island High School serves the four towns of Mount Desert Island, plus the outlying islands of Swans Island and the town of Cranberry Isles.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The school also serves students from towns such as Trenton, Hancock, Lamoine and Mariaville on the mainland.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The College of the Atlantic is located in Bar Harbor, on Route 3.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Bar Harbor's main access road, from the north or south, is State Route 3, which is the coastal Eden Street taken from the Trenton Bridge.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Upon entering the town limits from the north, Route 3 turns east onto Mount Desert Street, before turning south onto Main Street at Bar Harbor's Village Green.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] It then circumnavigates the eastern portion of Mount Desert Island.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Two other streets link Route 3 to Main Street: West Street (the first visitors from the north see) and Cottage Street.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Another principal road, Eagle Lake Road, leads west, from its intersection with Eden Street, Mount Desert Street and Kebo Street, into the national park.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The town is served by the Hancock County–Bar Harbor Airport, which provides year-round nonstop flights to Boston, Massachusetts.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Bar Harbor is the western terminus for *The CAT*, a high-speed summer ferry service across the Gulf of Maine to Yarmouth, Nova Scotia, Canada, operated by Bay Ferries.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The 3.5-hour route returned to service in 2022 after previously operating from 1955 to 2009.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Downeast Windjammer Cruise Lines operates regular summer ferry service across Frenchman Bay between Bar Harbor and Winter Harbor.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The population of Bar Harbor, and Mount Desert Island generally, increases dramatically from May through October with "seasonal" residents and tourists.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Many come for Acadia National Park, with its hiking trails and carriage roads, providing opportunities for biking, bird watching, and mountain climbing, with Cadillac Mountain being the highest point on the Atlantic seaboard.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Maritime tours are available, on a wide variety of boats, introducing visitors to puffins, whales, seals, seabirds, lighthouses, even lobsters, illustrating the working waterfront side of Bar Harbor.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The town has many historic houses, including large "cottages" along the shore, often converted to other uses today.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] To protect its housing supply for residents, citizens voted in 2021 to cap the number of vacation rentals in Bar Harbor.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] In 2012, the American Planning Association named the Village Green one of their top ten Great Places in America for Public Spaces.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Cruise ships visit Bar Harbor from May through October (most in September and October), with 154 ship visits and more than 222,000 passengers in 2018.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] The forecast for 2019 was 176 ship visits and more than 254,000 passengers.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] In November 2022, concerned about crowding and overtourism, the citizens of Bar Harbor voted for a citizens' initiative to cap cruise ship disembarkations to 1,000 per day.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Mount Desert Island Ice Cream, ranked among the best ice cream shops in the country, made the news in 2010 when President Obama and his family made a surprise visit for a treat.
[src:anecdata-org/bar-harbor-maine] Ben & Bill's Chocolate Emporium, with its lobster-flavored ice cream and lobster statue, is a popular stop.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] The colour of *C. maenas* varies greatly, from green to brown, grey, or red.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] This variation has a genetic component, but is largely due to local environmental factors.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In particular, individuals which delay moulting become red-coloured rather than green.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Red individuals are stronger and more aggressive, but are less tolerant of environmental stresses, such as low salinity or hypoxia.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Juvenile crabs on average display greater patterning than adults.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In Australia, *C. maenas* was first reported "in the late 1800s" in Port Phillip Bay, Victoria, although the species was probably introduced as early as the 1850s.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] It has since spread along the southeastern and southwestern seaboards, reaching New South Wales in 1971, South Australia in 1976 and Tasmania in 1993.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] One specimen was found in Western Australia in 1965, but no further discoveries have been reported in the area since.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Appearances of *C. maenas* have been recorded in Brazil, Panama, Hawaii, Madagascar, the Red Sea, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, and Myanmar; however, these have not resulted in invasions, but remain isolated findings.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Japan has been invaded by a related crab, either *Carcinus aestuarii* or a hybrid of *C. aestuarii* and *C. maenas*.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Based on the ecological conditions, *C. maenas* could eventually extend its range to colonise the Pacific Coast of North America from Baja California to Alaska.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In 2019, *C. maenas* was first found in Lummi Bay, Lummi Indian Reservation, Whatcom County, Washington, United States.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] The Lummi Nation began trapping and removing the crabs in an effort to get rid of them.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Then in 2020, hundreds were found in traps, and more intensive trapping clearly will be necessary to keep their numbers down.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Over a 19-year study concluding in 2020, Oregon's Coos Bay was found to have an established and increasing population.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] While in 2020, fewer than 3,000 were trapped, more than 79,000 were caught in 2021.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] This led the Lummi Indian Business Council to declare a disaster in November 2021 and the Washington Department of Fish and Wildlife to request emergency funding from the governor.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In 2025, the complete genome of *Carcinus maenas* was sequenced, providing a valuable foundation for investigating the genetic factors that contribute to this crab's global invasion success.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Females can produce more than 400,000 eggs, and larvae develop offshore in several stages before their final moult to juvenile crabs in the intertidal zone.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Young crabs live among seaweeds and seagrasses, such as *Posidonia oceanica*, until they reach adulthood.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] To protect itself against predators, *C. maenas* uses different camouflage strategies depending on its habitat; crabs in mudflats try to resemble their surroundings with colours similar to the mud, while crabs in rock pools use disruptive coloration.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Due to its potentially harmful effects on ecosystems, various efforts have been made to control introduced populations of *C. maenas* around the world.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In Edgartown, Massachusetts, a bounty was levied in 1995 for catching *C. maenas*, to protect local shellfish, and 10 tons were caught.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Some evidence shows that the native blue crab in eastern North America, *Callinectes sapidus*, is able to control populations of *C. maenas*; numbers of the two species are negatively correlated, and *C. maenas* is not found in the Chesapeake Bay, where *C. sapidus* is most frequent.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] On the west coast of North America, *C. maenas* appears to be limited to upper estuarine habitats, in part because of predation by native rock crabs (*Romaleon antennarium* and *Cancer productus*) and competition for shelter with a native shore crab, *Hemigrapsus oregonensis*.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Host specificity testing has recently been conducted on *Sacculina carcini*, a parasitic barnacle, as a potential biological control agent of *C. maenas*.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In the laboratory, *Sacculina* settled on, infected, and killed native California crabs, including the Dungeness crab, *Metacarcinus magister* (formerly *Cancer magister*), and the shore crabs *Hemigrapsus nudus*, *Hemigrapsus oregonensis* and *Pachygrapsus crassipes*.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Dungeness crabs were the most vulnerable of the tested native species to settlement and infection by the parasite.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Although *Sacculina* did not mature in any of the native crabs, developing reproductive sacs were observed inside a few *M. magister* and *H. oregonensis* crabs.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Any potential benefits of using *Sacculina* to control *C. maenas* on the west coast of North America would need to be weighed against these potential nontarget impacts.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In its native range, European green crab is mostly used as an ingredient in soups and sauces.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] However, the closely related Mediterranean green crab (*C. aestuarii*) has a thriving culinary market in Italy, where fishermen known as *moecante* cultivate soft-shell green crabs (*moeche* in Venetian, *moleche* in Italian) and sell hard-shell crabs for their roe (*masinette*).
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Several groups in New England have successfully adapted these methods to produce soft-shell green crabs from the invasive species.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In New England where invasive green crab populations are high, various groups have looked into using green crabs in cuisine.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In 2019, *The Green Crab Cookbook* was released; it included recipes for soft-shell green crab, green crab roe, green crab stock, and green crab meat.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] One of the book's co-authors went on to found Greencrab.org, an organization dedicated to developing culinary markets for the invasive green crab.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In addition to partnering with local chefs and wholesalers for supply chain development and market studies, Greencrab.org has continued to develop green crab recipes and processing techniques.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Researchers at the University of Maine have actively been developing value-added green crab products, with the goals of driving business interest, stimulating a commercial green crab fishery, and alleviating predation effects.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Specifically, one study evaluated the consumer acceptability of empanadas (fried, stuffed pastries), which contained varying amounts of green crab mince meat.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] The empanadas were rated between "like slightly" and "like moderately" for overall acceptability by a consumer panel (*n*=87).
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Furthermore, about two-thirds of the panelists would "probably" or "definitely" buy the empanadas if available locally.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Additionally, the same researchers developed a patty product made from green crab mince meat using restructuring additives (transglutaminase, dried egg white, isolated soy protein).
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Although a successful green crab patty was developed, the restructuring additives may have had greater functionality in a raw crab meat system, as opposed to the fully cooked mince that was used in the present study.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] The results from both studies are considered promising, especially considering that these were initial rounds of green crab product development.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In the past, Legal Sea Foods, an East Coast restaurant chain, experimented with green crabs, creating a green crab stock in their test kitchen during the winter of 2015.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In June 2022, Tamworth Distilling, a New Hampshire distillery, teamed up with the University of New Hampshire's NH Green Crab Project to develop House of Tamworth Crab Trapper, which is billed as being "made with a bourbon base steeped with a custom crab, corn, and spice blend mixture".
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] The lectotype chosen for the species came from Marstrand, Sweden, but it is assumed to have been lost.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In 1814, writing for *The Edinburgh Encyclopaedia*, William Elford Leach erected a new genus, *Carcinus* to hold this species alone (making it the type species of the genus, by monotypy).
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] In 1847, Nardo described a distinct subspecies occurring in the Mediterranean Sea, which is now recognised as a distinct species, *C. aestuarii*.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Particular amino acids in particular signaling peptides of *C. maenas* are protonated by pH changes currently (as of 2020) occurring or likely to be reached in the course of future climate change.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] This significantly alters peptide structure and peptide-mediated behaviours (brood care and egg ventilation requiring about 10 times the normal peptide concentration).
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] The requirement of higher concentration may be due to lowered binding affinity in the sensory epithelium.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] The usual decrease in extracellular chloride due to increased extracellular bicarbonate is avoided if *C. maenas* is first acclimated to the increased pCO2.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] While this may be due to the already-high extracellular chloride levels in this species, it may instead be because moderately higher pCO2 increases these levels through some unrelated mechanism.
[src:anecdata-org/carcinus-maenas] Changes in pH due to sodium and magnesium can alter extracellular iron concentrations.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The Association aims to expand the reach, relevance, and impact of science and research in the United States and internationally.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The CSA was founded in 2013 in the United States and was recognized as a charitable organization with a 501c3 designated status in June 2017.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The concept for the Citizen Science Association originated at the Public Participation for Scientific Research Conference in 2012 held in conjunction with the Ecological Society of America conference in Portland, Oregon.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] Through a series of NSF grants (DRL-0610363, DRL-1020909, and DRL-0813135) the network of citizen science projects and professionals was further developed and the Citizen Science Association formation as an official organization developed along with a website.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The Cornell Lab of Ornithology hosted the beginning of the Association web content and the Schoodic Institute helped launch the organization and is a continuing fiscal sponsor the CSA.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The CSA was renamed as the *Association for Advancing Participatory Sciences* in April 2024.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The association holds an annual professional conference called the Conference for Advancing the Participatory Sciences.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The conference brings together practitioners and researchers to discuss best practices in citizen science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The association has a memorandum of understanding for collaboration and coordination with peer organizations in other countries.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] These include the European Citizen Science Association, the Australian Citizen Science Association, and the developing communities and associations in Asia (CitizenScience.Asia) and Africa.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The United Nations officially recognised the Citizen Science Association and is working with the Citizen Science Global Partnership on how citizen science can best be applied to help tackle the Sustainable Development Goals.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The association has an online, open-access, peer-reviewed journal called *Citizen Science: Theory and Practice* published by Ubiquity Press.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The journal provides a venue for researchers and practitioners to share best practices in conceiving, developing, implementing, evaluating, and sustaining projects that facilitate public participation in scientific endeavors in any discipline.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The journal publishes research reports, reviews and synthesis, case studies, essays, methods, and meeting reports.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] The association’s working groups focus on priority areas of the science and practice of citizen science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-association] As of February 2020 the following nine working groups have formed.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The applications and functions of citizen science in research projects are multifaceted.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen science can be used as a methodology in which public volunteers help in data collection and classification, thereby improving the scientific community's capacity.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen science observations can be used to uncover general trends in native habitats across broad spatial and temporal scales, extending data collection beyond the capacity of individual researchers.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] These observations can then be integrated with findings from designed experiments to provide a more complete understanding of natural variation and ecological processes.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen science can also involve more direct involvement from the public, with communities initiating projects researching environment and health hazards within their own communities.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Participation in citizen science projects also educates the public about the scientific process and increases awareness about different topics.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Some schools incorporate citizen science projects as part of their teaching curricula for this very purpose.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The first use of the term "citizen science" appeared in a January 1989 issue of the *MIT Technology Review*, which featured three community-based labs studying environmental issues.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In the 21st century, the number of citizen science projects, publications, and funding opportunities has increased.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen science has been used more over time, a trend helped by technological advancements.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Digital citizen science platforms, such as Zooniverse and iNaturalist, store large amounts of data for many projects and are a place where volunteers can learn how to contribute to projects.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] For some projects, participants are instructed to collect and enter data, such as the species they observed, into large digital global databases.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] For other projects, participants help classify data on digital platforms.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen science data is also being used to develop machine learning algorithms.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] An example is using volunteer-classified images to train machine learning algorithms to identify species.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] While global participation and global databases are found on online platforms, the uniformity of data from contributors across different locations is not guaranteed.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Concerns over potential data quality issues in citizen science projects, including measurement errors and biases, are recognized in the scientific community.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] However, statistical solutions and best practices are available to assist in addressing these concerns.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The term "citizen science" has multiple origins, as well as differing concepts.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] "Citizen" is used in the general sense, as meaning in "citizen of the world", or the general public, rather than the legal term citizen of sovereign countries.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] It was first defined independently in the mid-1990s by Rick Bonney in the United States and Alan Irwin in the United Kingdom.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Alan Irwin, a British sociologist, defines citizen science as "developing concepts of scientific citizenship which foregrounds the necessity of opening up science and science policy processes to the public".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Irwin sought to reclaim two dimensions of the relationship between citizens and science: 1) that science should be responsive to citizens' concerns and needs; and 2) that citizens themselves could produce reliable scientific knowledge.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The American ornithologist Rick Bonney, unaware of Irwin's work, defined citizen science as projects in which nonscientists, such as amateur birdwatchers, voluntarily contributed scientific data.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] This describes a more limited role for citizens in scientific research than Irwin's conception of the term.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The terms *citizen science* and *citizen scientists* entered the Oxford English Dictionary (*OED*) in June 2014.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] "Citizen science" is defined as "scientific work undertaken by members of the general public, often in collaboration with or under the direction of professional scientists and scientific institutions".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The first use of the term "citizen scientist" can be found in the magazine *New Scientist* in an article about ufology from October 1979.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Muki Haklay cites, from a policy report for the Wilson Center entitled "Citizen Science and Policy: A European Perspective", an alternate first use of the term "citizen science" by R.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Kerson in the magazine *MIT Technology Review* from January 1989.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Quoting from the Wilson Center report: "The new form of engagement in science received the name 'citizen science'.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen science may be performed by individuals, teams, or networks of volunteers.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen scientists often partner with professional scientists to achieve common goals.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Large volunteer networks often allow scientists to accomplish tasks that would be too expensive or time-consuming to accomplish through other means.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Many citizen-science projects serve education and outreach goals.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] These projects may be designed for a formal classroom environment or an informal education environment such as museums.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen science has evolved over the past four decades.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Recent projects place more emphasis on scientifically sound practices and measurable goals for public education.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Modern citizen science differs from its historical forms primarily in the access for, and subsequent scale of, public participation; technology is credited as one of the main drivers of the recent explosion of citizen science activity.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In March 2015, the Office of Science and Technology Policy published a factsheet entitled "Empowering Students and Others through Citizen Science and Crowdsourcing".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Quoting: "Citizen science and crowdsourcing projects are powerful tools for providing students with skills needed to excel in science, technology, engineering, and math (STEM).
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Volunteers in citizen science, for example, gain hands-on experience doing real science, and in many cases take that learning outside of the traditional classroom setting".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The National Academies of Science cites SciStarter as a platform offering access to more than 2,700 citizen science projects and events, as well as helping interested parties access tools that facilitate project participation.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In May 2016, a new open-access journal was started by the Citizen Science Association along with Ubiquity Press called *Citizen Science: Theory and Practice* (*CS:T&P*).
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Quoting from the editorial article titled "The Theory and Practice of Citizen Science: Launching a New Journal", "*CS:T&P* provides the space to enhance the quality and impact of citizen science efforts by deeply exploring the citizen science concept in all its forms and across disciplines.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In February 2020, Timber Press, an imprint of Workman Publishing Company, published *The Field Guide to Citizen Science* as a practical guide for anyone interested in getting started with citizen science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Other definitions for citizen science have also been proposed.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Scientists and scholars who have used other definitions include Frank N. von Hippel, Stephen Schneider, Neal Lane and Jon Beckwith.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Other alternative terminologies proposed are "civic science" and "civic scientist".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen science initiatives are commonly categorized according to the level of involvement of the citizen scientists.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Towards the lower end of involvement, terms such as crowdsourcing or contributory citizen science describe that citizen scientists contribute observations, collect data or merely offer computing power or install sensors to measure environmental variables.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Towards the higher end of involvement, "extreme citizen science" and co-creation are terms used to describe initiatives in which citizen scientists are involved in decisions influencing the goal and research methods or even lead research initiatives.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In a Smart City era, Citizen Science relies on various web-based tools, such as WebGIS, and becomes Cyber Citizen Science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Some projects, such as SETI@home, use the Internet to take advantage of distributed computing.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Computation tasks are performed by volunteers' computers and require little involvement beyond initial setup.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] There is disagreement as to whether these projects should be classified as citizen science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The astrophysicist and Galaxy Zoo co-founder Kevin Schawinski stated: "We prefer to call this [Galaxy Zoo] citizen science because it's a better description of what you're doing; you're a regular citizen but you're doing science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Crowd sourcing sounds a bit like, well, you're just a member of the crowd and you're not; you're our collaborator.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Compared to SETI@home, "Galaxy Zoo volunteers do real work.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] They're not just passively running something on their computer and hoping that they'll be the first person to find aliens.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen policy may be another result of citizen science initiatives.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The general public's involvement in scientific projects has become a means of encouraging curiosity and greater understanding of science while providing an unprecedented engagement between professional scientists and the general public.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In a research report published by the U.S.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] National Park Service in 2008, Brett Amy Thelen and Rachel K.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The question of data accuracy, in particular, remains open.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] John Losey, who created the Lost Ladybug citizen science project, has argued that the cost-effectiveness of citizen science data can outweigh data quality issues, if properly managed.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Simmons published a study in the journal *Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment* called "Assessing Data Quality in Citizen Science".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The abstract describes how ecological and environmental citizen science projects have enormous potential to advance science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen science projects can influence policy and guide resource management by producing datasets that are otherwise not feasible to generate.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In the section "In a Nutshell" (pg3), four condensed conclusions are stated.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] They conclude that as citizen science continues to grow and mature, a key metric of project success they expect to see will be a growing awareness of data quality.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] A study of Canadian lepidoptera datasets published in 2018 compared the use of a professionally curated dataset of butterfly specimen records with four years of data from a citizen science program, eButterfly.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The eButterfly dataset was used as it was determined to be of high quality because of the expert vetting process used on site, and there already existed a dataset covering the same geographic area consisting of specimen data, much of it institutional.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The authors note that, in this case, citizen science data provides both novel and complementary information to the specimen data.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Five new species were reported from the citizen science data, and geographic distribution information was improved for over 80% of species in the combined dataset when citizen science data was included.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Several recent studies have begun to explore the accuracy of citizen science projects and how to predict accuracy based on variables like expertise of practitioners.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] This provided insight into possible problems with processes like this which include, "discriminatory power and guessing behaviour".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The researchers determined that methods for rating the citizen scientists themselves based on skill level and expertise might make studies they conduct more easy to analyze.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Studies that are simple in execution are where citizen science excels, particularly in the field of conservation biology and ecology.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] For example, in 2019, Sumner et al. compared the data of vespid wasp distributions collected by citizen scientists with the 4-decade, long-term dataset established by the BWARS.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] They set up the Big Wasp Survey from 26 August to 10 September 2017, inviting citizen scientists to trap wasps and send them for identification by experts where data was recorded.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The results of this study showed that the campaign garnered over 2,000 citizen scientists participating in data collection, identifying over 6,600 wasps.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] This experiment provides strong evidence that citizen science can generate potentially high-quality data comparable to that of expert data collection, within a shorter time frame.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Although the experiment was to originally test the strength of citizen science, the team also learned more about Vespidae biology and species distribution in the United Kingdom.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] With this study, the simple procedure enabled citizen science to be executed in a successful manner.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Cohn describes that volunteers can be trained to use equipment and process data, especially considering that a large proportion of citizen scientists are individuals who are already well-versed in the field of science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The demographics of participants in citizen science projects are overwhelmingly White adults, of above-average income, having a university degree.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Other groups of volunteers include conservationists, outdoor enthusiasts, and amateur scientists.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] As such, citizen scientists are generally individuals with a pre-understanding of the scientific method and how to conduct sensible and just scientific analysis.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In September 2015, ECSA published its *Ten Principles of Citizen Science*, which have been developed by the "Sharing best practice and building capacity" working group of ECSA, led by the Natural History Museum, London with input from many members of the association.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The medical ethics of internet crowdsourcing has been questioned by Graber & Graber in the *Journal of Medical Ethics*.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In particular, they analyse the effect of games and the crowdsourcing project Foldit.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] They conclude: "games can have possible adverse effects, and that they manipulate the user into participation".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In March 2019, the online journal *Citizen Science: Theory and Practice* launched a collection of articles on the theme of Ethical Issues in Citizen Science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The articles are introduced with (quoting): "Citizen science can challenge existing ethical norms because it falls outside of customary methods of ensuring that research is conducted ethically.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] What ethical issues arise when engaging the public in research?
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In June 2019, *East Asian Science, Technology and Society: An International Journal* (EASTS) published an issue titled "Citizen Science: Practices and Problems" which contains 15 articles/studies on citizen science, including many relevant subjects of which ethics is one.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Use of citizen science volunteers as *de facto* unpaid laborers by some commercial ventures have been criticized as exploitative.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Ethics in citizen science in the health and welfare field, has been discussed in terms of protection versus participation.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Public involvement researcher Kristin Liabo writes that health researcher might, in light of their ethics training, be inclined to exclude vulnerable individuals from participation, to protect them from harm.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] However, she argues these groups are already likely to be excluded from participation in other arenas, and that participation can be empowering and a possibility to gain life skills that these individuals need.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Whether or not to become involved should be a decision these individuals should be involved in and not a researcher decision.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] As citizen science becomes increasingly influenced by digital platforms and sensors, governance questions go beyond research ethics to include data protection law and community control over reuse.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Practical guidance for citizen science therefore increasingly requires early planning for lawful data handling, clear allocation of responsibilities, and transparency about data flows across collection, storage, and sharing.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] A second governance challenge concerns power asymmetries in open data.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Because volunteers often produce data while institutions handle and publish it, decisions about openness, attribution, and access restrictions can include unequal priorities and certain vulnerabilities.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Ethical open-data practice in citizen science is therefore frequently framed as a matter of data governance, not only technical quality.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] These concerns also extend to environmental monitoring where data may be politically sensitive (e.g., pollution exposure, land use, biodiversity decline).
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Related international policy discussions on open science explicitly point out that openness should not overrule privacy, equity, or indigenous rights over traditional knowledge.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In the research paper "Can citizen science enhance public understanding of science?" by Bonney et al.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] 2016, statistics which analyse the economic worth of citizen science are used, drawn from two papers: **i)** Sauermann and Franzoni 2015, and **ii)** Theobald et al.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In "Crowd science user contribution patterns and their implications" by Sauermann and Franzoni (2015), seven projects from the Zooniverse web portal are used to estimate the monetary value of the citizen science that had taken place.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The seven projects are: Solar Stormwatch, Galaxy Zoo Supernovae, Galaxy Zoo Hubble, Moon Zoo, Old Weather, The Milky Way Project and Planet Hunters.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Using data from 180 days in 2010, they find a total of 100,386 users participated, contributing 129,540 hours of unpaid work.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Estimating at a rate of $12 an hour (an undergraduate research assistant's basic wage), the total contributions amount to $1,554,474, an average of $222,068 per project.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The range over the seven projects was from $22,717 to $654,130.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In "Global change and local solutions: Tapping the unrealized potential of citizen science for biodiversity research" by Theobald et al.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] 2015, the authors surveyed 388 unique biodiversity-based projects.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Worldwide participation in citizen science continues to grow.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] A list of the top five citizen science communities compiled by Marc Kuchner and Kristen Erickson in July 2018 shows a total of 3.75 million participants, although there is likely substantial overlap between the communities.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] There have been studies published which examine the place of citizen science within education.(e.g.) Teaching aids can include books and activity or lesson plans.(e.g.).
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] From the journal *Democracy and Education*, an article entitled: "Lessons Learned from Citizen Science in the Classroom" by authors Gray, Nicosia and Jordan (GNJ; 2012) gives a response to a study by Mueller, Tippins and Bryan (MTB) called "The Future of Citizen Science".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In 2014, a study was published called "Citizen Science and Lifelong Learning" by R.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Edwards in the journal *Studies in the Education of Adults*.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Edwards begins by writing in the abstract that citizen science projects have expanded over recent years and engaged citizen scientists and professionals in diverse ways.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] He continues: "Yet there has been little educational exploration of such projects to date." He describes that "there has been limited exploration of the educational backgrounds of adult contributors to citizen science".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Edwards explains that citizen science contributors are referred to as volunteers, citizens or as amateurs.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In the journal *Microbiology and Biology Education* a study was published by Shah and Martinez (2015) called "Current Approaches in Implementing Citizen Science in the Classroom".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] They begin by writing in the abstract that citizen science is a partnership between inexperienced amateurs and trained scientists.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The authors continue: "With recent studies showing a weakening in scientific competency of American students, incorporating citizen science initiatives in the curriculum provides a means to address deficiencies".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] They argue that combining traditional and innovative methods can help provide a practical experience of science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] In November 2017, authors Mitchell, Triska and Liberatore published a study in *PLOS One* titled "Benefits and Challenges of Incorporating Citizen Science into University Education".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] The authors begin by stating in the abstract that citizen scientists contribute data with the expectation that it will be used.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] It reports that citizen science has been used for first year university students as a means to experience research.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] They continue: "Surveys of more than 1500 students showed that their environmental engagement increased significantly after participating in data collection and data analysis." However, only a third of students agreed that data collected by citizen scientists was reliable.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] A positive outcome of this was that the students were more careful of their own research.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p01] Citizen science has also been described as challenging the "traditional hierarchies and structures of knowledge creation".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] While citizen science developed at the end of the 20th century, characteristics of citizen science are not new.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Prior to the 20th century, science was often the pursuit of gentleman scientists, amateur or self-funded researchers such as Sir Isaac Newton, Benjamin Franklin, and Charles Darwin.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Women citizen scientists from before the 20th century include Florence Nightingale who "perhaps better embodies the radical spirit of citizen science".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Before the professionalization of science by the end of the 19th century, most pursued scientific projects as an activity rather than a profession itself, an example being amateur naturalists in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] During the British colonization of North America, American Colonists recorded the weather, offering much of the information now used to estimate climate data and climate change during this time period.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] These people included John Campanius Holm, who recorded storms in the mid-1600s, as well as George Washington, Thomas Jefferson, and Benjamin Franklin who tracked weather patterns during America's founding.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Their work focused on identifying patterns by amassing their data and that of their peers and predecessors, rather than specific professional knowledge in scientific fields.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Some consider these individuals as the progenitors of the citizen scientist concept, while others ascribe this designation to prominent figures such as Leonardo da Vinci and Charles Darwin.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] However, there are also those who perceive citizen science as a distinct movement that developed later on, building on the preceding history of science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] However, by the mid-20th century, the scientific community was dominated by researchers employed by universities and government research laboratories.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] By the 1970s, this transformation was being called into question.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Philosopher Paul Feyerabend called for a "democratization of science".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Biochemist Erwin Chargaff advocated a return to science by nature-loving amateurs in the tradition of Descartes, Newton, Leibniz, Buffon, and Darwin.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] This approach would prioritize the contributions of "amateurship instead of money-biased technical bureaucrats".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] A 2016 study indicates that the largest impact of citizen science is evident in research domains such as biology, conservation, and ecology.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The primary utilization of citizen science is as a methodology for data collection and classification.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Astronomy has long been a field where amateurs have contributed throughout time, all the way up to the present day.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Collectively, amateur astronomers observe a variety of celestial objects and phenomena sometimes with equipment that they build themselves.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Common targets of amateur astronomers include the Moon, planets, stars, comets, meteor showers, and a variety of deep-sky objects such as star clusters, galaxies, and nebulae.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Observations of comets and stars are also used to measure the local level of artificial skyglow.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] One branch of amateur astronomy, amateur astrophotography, involves the taking of photos of the night sky.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Many amateurs like to specialize in the observation of particular objects, types of objects, or types of events that interest them.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The American Association of Variable Star Observers has gathered data on variable stars for educational and professional analysis since 1911 and promotes participation beyond its membership on its Citizen Sky website.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Project PoSSUM is a relatively new organization, started in March 2012, which trains citizen scientists of many ages to go on polar suborbital missions.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] On these missions, they study noctilucent clouds with remote sensing, which reveals interesting clues about changes in the upper atmosphere and the ozone due to climate change.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] This is a form of citizen science which trains younger generations to be ambitious, participating in intriguing astronomy and climate change science projects even without a professional degree.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Butterfly counts have a long tradition of involving individuals in the study of butterflies' range and their relative abundance.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Two long-running programs are the UK Butterfly Monitoring Scheme (started in 1976) and the North American Butterfly Association's Butterfly Count Program (started in 1975).
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] There are various protocols for monitoring butterflies and different organizations support one or more of transects, counts and/or opportunistic sightings. eButterfly is an example of a program designed to capture any of the three types of counts for observers in North America.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Species-specific programs also exist, with monarchs the prominent example.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Two examples of this involve the counting of monarch butterflies during the fall migration to overwintering sites in Mexico: (1) Monarch Watch is a continent-wide project, while (2) the Cape May Monarch Monitoring Project is an example of a local project.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen science projects have become increasingly focused on providing benefits to scientific research.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The North American Bird Phenology Program (historically called the Bird Migration and Distribution records) may have been the earliest collective effort of citizens collecting ornithological information in the U.S.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The program, dating back to 1883, was started by Wells Woodbridge Cooke.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Cooke established a network of observers around North America to collect bird migration records.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The Audubon Society's Christmas Bird Count, which began in 1900, is another example of a long-standing tradition of citizen science which has persisted to the present day, now containing a collection of six million handwritten migration observer cards that date back to the 19th century.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Participants input this data into an online database for analysis.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen scientists help gather data that will be analyzed by professional researchers, and can be used to produce bird population and biodiversity indicators.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Raptor migration research relies on the data collected by the hawkwatching community.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] This mostly volunteer group counts migrating accipiters, buteos, falcons, harriers, kites, eagles, osprey, vultures and other raptors at hawk sites throughout North America during the spring and fall seasons.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The daily data is uploaded to hawkcount.org where it can be viewed by professional scientists and the public.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Other programs in North America include Project FeederWatch, which is affiliated with the Cornell Lab of Ornithology.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Such indices can be useful tools to inform management, resource allocation, policy and planning.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] For example, European breeding bird survey data provide input for the Farmland Bird Index, adopted by the European Union as a structural indicator of sustainable development.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] This provides a cost-effective alternative to government monitoring.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Similarly, data collected by citizen scientists as part of BirdLife Australia's has been analysed to produce the first-ever Australian Terrestrial Bird Indices.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] In the UK, the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds collaborated with a children's TV show to create a national birdwatching day in 1979; the campaign has continued for over 40 years and in 2024, over 600,000 people counted almost 10 million birds during the Big Garden Birdwatch weekend.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Most recently, more programs have sprung up worldwide, including NestWatch, a bird species monitoring program which tracks data on reproduction.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] This might include studies on when and how often nesting occurs, counting eggs laid and how many hatch successfully, and what proportion of hatchlings survive infancy.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Participation in this program is extremely easy for the general public to join.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Using the recently created nest watch app which is available on almost all devices, anyone can begin to observe their local species, recording results every 3 to 4 days within the app.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] This forms a continually-growing database which researchers can view and utilize to understand trends within specific bird populations.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The concept of citizen science has been extended to the ocean environment for characterizing ocean dynamics and tracking marine debris.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] For example, the mobile app Marine Debris Tracker is a joint partnership of National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and the University of Georgia.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Long term sampling efforts such as the continuous plankton recorder has been fitted on ships of opportunity since 1931.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Plankton collection by sailors and subsequent genetic analysis was pioneered in 2013 by Indigo V Expeditions as a way to better understand marine microbial structure and function.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen science in coral reef studies developed in the 21st century.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Underwater photography has become more popular since the development of moderate priced digital cameras with waterproof housings in the early 2000s, resulting on millions of pictures posted every year on various websites and social media.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] This mass of documentation has great scientific potential, as millions of tourists possess a much superior coverage power than professional scientists, who cannot spend so much time in the field.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] As a consequence, several participative sciences programs have been developed, supported by geotagging and identification web sites such as iNaturalist.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The *Monitoring through many eyes* project collates thousands of underwater images of the Great Barrier Reef and provides an interface for elicitation of reef health indicators.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) also offers opportunities for volunteer participation.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] By taking measurements in The United States' National Marine Sanctuaries, citizens contribute data to marine biology projects.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] In 2016, NOAA benefited from 137,000 hours of research.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] There also exist protocols for auto-organization and self-teaching aimed at biodiversity-interested snorkelers, in order for them to turn their observations into sound scientific data, available for research.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] This kind of approach has been successfully used in Réunion island, allowing for tens of new records and even new species.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Aquarium hobbyists and their respective organizations are very passionate about fish conservation and often more knowledgeable about specific fish species and groups than scientific researchers.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen scientists also work to monitor and conserve amphibian populations.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] One recent project is FrogWatch USA, organized by the Association of Zoos and Aquariums.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Participants are invited to educate themselves on their local wetlands and help to save amphibian populations by reporting the data on the calls of local frogs and toads.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The project already has over 150,000 observations from more than 5000 contributors.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Participants are trained by program coordinators to identify calls and utilize this training to report data they find between February and August of each "monitoring season".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Data is used to monitor diversity, invasion, and long-term shifts in population health within these frog and toad communities.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Reef Life Survey is a marine life monitoring programme based in Hobart, Tasmania.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The project uses recreational divers that have been trained to make fish and invertebrate counts, using an approximate 50 m constant depth transect of tropical and temperate reefs, which might include coral reefs.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Reef Life Survey is international in its scope, but the data collectors are predominantly from Australia.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The database is available to marine ecology researchers, and is used by several marine protected area managements in Australia, New Zealand, American Samoa and the eastern Pacific.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Its results have also been included in the Australian Ocean DATA Network.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Farmer participation in experiments has a long tradition in agricultural science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] There are many opportunities for citizen engagement in different parts of food systems.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen science is actively used for crop variety selection for climate adaptation, involving thousands of farmers.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen science has also played a role in furthering sustainable agriculture.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen science has a long tradition in natural science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Today, citizen science projects can also be found in various fields of science like art history.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] For example, the Zooniverse project AnnoTate is a transcription tool developed to enable volunteers to read and transcribe the personal papers of British-born and émigré artists.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The papers are drawn from the Tate Archive.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Another example of citizen science in art history is ARTigo.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] ARTigo collects semantic data on artworks from the footprints left by players of games featuring artwork images.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] From these footprints, ARTigo automatically builds a semantic search engine for artworks.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen science has made significant contributions to the analysis of biodiversity across the world.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] A majority of data collected has been focused primarily on species occurrence, abundance and phenology, with birds being primarily the most popular group observed.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] There is growing efforts to expand the use of citizen science across other fields.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Past data on biodiversity has had limitations in the quantity of data to make any meaningful broad connections to losses in biodiversity.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Recruiting citizens already out in the field opens a tremendous amount of new data.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] For example, thousands of farmers reporting the changes in biodiversity in their farms over many years has provided a large amount of relevant data concerning the effect of different farming methods on biodiversity.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Another example is WomSAT, a citizen science project that collects data on wombat roadkill and sarcoptic mange incidence and distribution, to support conservation efforts for the species.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen science can be used to great effect in addition to the usual scientific methods in biodiversity monitoring.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The typical active method of species detection is able to collect data on the broad biodiversity of areas while citizen science approaches has shown to be more effective at identifying invasive species.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] In combination, this provides an effective strategy of monitoring the changes in biodiversity of ecosystems.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] In the research fields of health and welfare, citizen science is often discussed in other terms, such as "public involvement", "user engagement", or "community member involvement".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] However the meaning is similar to citizen science, with the exception that citizens are not often involved in collecting data but more often involved in prioritisation of research ideas and improving methodology, e.g. survey questions.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] In the last decades, researchers and funders have gained awareness of the benefits from involving citizens in the research work, but the involvement of citizens in a meaningful way is not a common practice.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] There is an ongoing discussion on how to evaluate citizen science in health and welfare research.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] One aspect to consider in citizen science in health and welfare, that stands out compared to in other academic fields, is *who* to involve.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] When research concerns human experiences, representation of a group becomes important.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] While it is commonly acknowledged that the people involved need to have lived experience of the concerned topic, representation is still an issue, and researchers are debating whether this is a useful concept in citizen science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Outside of the older patient and public involvement tradition, there are also efforts to bring the newer citizen science efforts to health and biomedical research.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] These efforts cover a broad spectrum of involvement and co-leadership of patients, including patient-led research, quantified self or personal science, as well as collaborative research efforts between researchers and patient-groups, often enabled by digital technology.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] A survey among European practitioners involved in health-related citizen science found that ethical challenges and achieving a balanced return on investment for patients and medical staff are common challenges.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Newer technologies have increased the options for citizen science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen scientists can build and operate their own instruments to gather data for their own experiments or as part of a larger project.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Examples include amateur radio, amateur astronomy, Six Sigma Projects, and Maker activities.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Scientist Joshua Pearce has advocated for the creation of open-source hardware based scientific equipment that both citizen scientists and professional scientists, which can be replicated by digital manufacturing techniques such as 3D printing.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Multiple studies have shown this approach radically reduces scientific equipment costs.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Examples of this approach include water testing, nitrate and other environmental testing, basic biology and optics.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Groups such as Public Lab, which is a community where citizen scientists can learn how to investigate environmental concerns using inexpensive DIY techniques, embody this approach.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Video technology is much used in scientific research.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The Citizen Science Center in the Nature Research Center wing of the North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences has exhibits on how to get involved in scientific research and become a citizen scientist.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] For example, visitors can observe birdfeeders at the Prairie Ridge Ecostation satellite facility via live video feed and record which species they see.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Since 2005, the Genographic Project has used the latest genetic technology to expand our knowledge of the human story, and its pioneering use of DNA testing to engage and involve the public in the research effort has helped to create a new breed of "citizen scientist".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Geno 2.0 expands the scope for citizen science, harnessing the power of the crowd to discover new details of human population history.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] This includes supporting, organization and dissemination of personal DNA testing.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Like amateur astronomy, citizen scientists encouraged by volunteer organizations like the International Society of Genetic Genealogy have provided valuable information and research to the professional scientific community.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] With unmanned aerial vehicles, further citizen science is enabled.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] One example is the ESA's AstroDrone smartphone app for gathering robotic data with the Parrot AR.Drone.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizens in Space (CIS), a project of the United States Rocket Academy, seeks to combine citizen science with citizen space exploration.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] CIS is training citizen astronauts to fly as payload operators on suborbital reusable spacecraft that are now in development.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] CIS will also be developing, and encouraging others to develop, citizen-science payloads to fly on suborbital vehicles.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] CIS has already acquired a contract for 10 flights on the Lynx suborbital vehicle, being developed by XCOR Aerospace, and plans to acquire additional flights on XCOR Lynx and other suborbital vehicles in the future.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The website *CitizenScience.gov* was started by the U.S. government to "accelerate the use of crowdsourcing and citizen science" in the United States.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Following the internet's rapid increase of citizen science projects, this site is one of the most prominent resource banks for citizen scientists and government supporters alike.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] It features three sections: a catalog of existing citizen science projects which are federally supported, a toolkit to help federal officials as they develop and maintain their future projects, and several other resources and projects.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] This was created as the result of a mandate within the Crowdsourcing and Citizen Science Act of 2016 (15 USC 3724).
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The Internet has been a boon to citizen science, particularly through gamification.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] One of the first Internet-based citizen science experiments was NASA's Clickworkers, which enabled the general public to assist in the classification of images, greatly reducing the time to analyze large data sets.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Another was the Citizen Science Toolbox, launched in 2003, of the Australian Coastal Collaborative Research Centre.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Mozak is a game in which players create 3D reconstructions from images of actual human and mouse neurons, helping to advance understanding of the brain.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] One of the largest citizen science games is *Eyewire*, a brain-mapping puzzle game developed at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology that now has over 200,000 players.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Another example is *Quantum Moves*, a game developed by the Center for Driven Community Research at Aarhus University, which uses online community efforts to solve quantum physics problems.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The solutions found by players can then be used in the lab to feed computational algorithms used in building a scalable quantum computer.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] More generally, Amazon's Mechanical Turk is frequently used in the creation, collection, and processing of data by paid citizens.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] There is controversy as to whether or not the data collected through such services is reliable, as it is subject to participants' desire for compensation.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] However, use of Mechanical Turk tends to quickly produce more diverse participant backgrounds, as well as comparably accurate data when compared to traditional collection methods.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The internet has also enabled citizen scientists to gather data to be analyzed by professional researchers.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen science networks are often involved in the observation of cyclic events of nature (phenology), such as effects of global warming on plant and animal life in different geographic areas, and in monitoring programs for natural-resource management.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] On BugGuide.Net, an online community of naturalists who share observations of arthropod, amateurs and professional researchers contribute to the analysis.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] By October 2022, BugGuide has over 1,886,513 images submitted by 47,732 contributors.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Not counting iNaturalist and eBird, the Zooniverse is home to the internet's largest, most popular and most successful citizen science projects.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The Zooniverse and the suite of projects it contains is produced, maintained and developed by the Citizen Science Alliance (CSA).
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The member institutions of the CSA work with many academic and other partners around the world to produce projects that use the efforts and ability of volunteers to help scientists and researchers deal with the flood of data that confronts them.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] On 29 June 2015, the Zooniverse released a new software version with a project-building tool allowing any registered user to create a project.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Project owners may optionally complete an approval process to have their projects listed on the Zooniverse site and promoted to the Zooniverse community.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] A NASA/JPL picture to the right gives an example from one of Zooniverse's projects The Milky Way Project.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] CrowdCrafting enables its participants to create and run projects where volunteers help with image classification, transcription, geocoding and more.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The platform is powered by PyBossa software, a free and open-source framework for crowdsourcing.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Project Soothe is a citizen science research project based at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The aim of this research is to create a bank of soothing images, submitted by members of the public, which can be used to help others through psychotherapy and research in the future.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Since 2015, Project Soothe has received over 600 soothing photographs from people in 23 countries.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Anyone aged 12 years or over is eligible to participate in this research in two ways: (1) By submitting soothing photos that they have taken with a description of why the images make them feel soothed (2) By rating the photos that have been submitted by people worldwide for their soothability.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The internet has allowed for many individuals to share and upload massive amounts of data.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Using the internet citizen observatories have been designed as a platform to both increase citizen participation and knowledge of their surrounding environment by collecting whatever relevant data is focused by the program.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The idea is making it easier and more exciting for citizens to get and stay involved in local data collection.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The invention of social media has aided in providing massive amounts of information from the public to create citizen science programs.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] In a case study by Andrea Liberatore, Erin Bowkett, Catriona J.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] MacLeod, Eric Spurr, and Nancy Longnecker, the New Zealand Garden Bird Survey is conducted as one such project with the aid of social media.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] It examines the influence of utilizing a Facebook group to collect data from citizen scientists as the researchers work on the project over the span of a year.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The authors claim that this use of social media greatly helps with the efficiency of this study and makes the atmosphere feel more communal.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The bandwidth and ubiquity afforded by smartphones has vastly expanded the opportunities for citizen science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Examples include iNaturalist, Chronolog, the San Francisco project, Mosquito Alert, the WildLab, Project Noah, and Aurorasurus.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Due to their ubiquity, for example, Twitter, Facebook, and smartphones have been useful for citizen scientists, having enabled them to discover and propagate a new type of aurora dubbed STEVE in 2016.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] There are also apps for monitoring birds, marine wildlife and other organisms, and the "Loss of the Night".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Chronolog, another citizen science initiative, uses smartphone photography to crowdsource environmental monitoring through timelapses.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] By positioning their cameras at designated photo stations and submitting images, participants contribute to long-term ecological records at parks and conservation sites across 48 U.S. states and 10 countries.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Restoration professionals and other land stewards use this data to measure ecosystem health and understand the effectiveness of conservation interventions like habitat restoration, controlled burns, removal of invasive species, planting of native species, and efforts to improve water quality.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] "The Crowd and the Cloud" is a four-part series broadcast during April 2017, which examines citizen science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] It shows how smartphones, computers and mobile technology enable regular citizens to become part of a 21st-century way of doing science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The programs also demonstrate how citizen scientists help professional scientists to advance knowledge, which helps speed up new discoveries and innovations.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The Crowd & The Cloud is based upon work supported by the U.S.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Since 1975, in order to improve earthquake detection and collect useful information, the European-Mediterranean Seismological Centre monitors the visits of earthquake eyewitnesses to its website and relies on Facebook and Twitter.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] More recently, they developed the LastQuake mobile application which notifies users about earthquakes occurring around the world, alerts people when earthquakes hit near them, gathers citizen seismologists' testimonies to estimate the felt ground shaking and possible damages.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen science has been used to provide valuable data in hydrology (catchment science), notably flood risk, water quality, and water resource management.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] A growth in internet use and smartphone ownership has allowed users to collect and share real-time flood-risk information using, for example, social media and web-based forms.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Although traditional data collection methods are well-established, citizen science is being used to fill the data gaps on a local level, and is therefore meaningful to individual communities.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Data collected from citizen science can also compare well to professionally collected data.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] It has been demonstrated that citizen science is particularly advantageous during a flash flood because the public are more likely to witness these rarer hydrological events than scientists.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Citizen science includes projects that help monitor plastics and their associated pollution.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] These include The Ocean Cleanup, #OneLess, The Big Microplastic Survey, EXXpedition and Alliance to End Plastic Waste.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Ellipsis seeks to map the distribution of litter using aerial data mapping by unmanned aerial vehicles and machine learning software.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] A Zooniverse project called The Plastic Tide (now finished) helped train an algorithm used by Ellipsis.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] While the idea of using mobile technology to aid this sensing is not new, creating devices and systems that can be used to aid regulation has not been straightforward.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] A group of citizen scientists in a community-led project targeting toxic smoke from wood burners in Bristol, has recorded 11 breaches of World Health Organization daily guidelines for ultra-fine particulate pollution over a period of six months.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] In a £7M programme funded by water regulator Ofwat, citizen scientists are being trained to test for pollution and over-abstraction in 10 river catchment areas in the UK.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Sensors will be used and the information gathered will be available in a central visualisation platform.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The project is led by The Rivers Trust and United Utilities and includes volunteers such as anglers testing the rivers they use.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] River water quality in the U.K. has been tested by a combined total of over 7,000 volunteers in so-called "blitzes" run over two weekends in 2024.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The research by the NGO Earthwatch Europe gathered data from 4,000 freshwater sites and used standardised testing equipment provide by the NGO and Imperial College.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The second blitz in October 2024 included testing for chemical pollutants, such as antibiotics, agricultural chemicals and pesticides.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Results from 4,531 volunteers showed that over 61% of the freshwater sites "were in a poor state because of high levels of the nutrients phosphate and nitrate, the main source of which is sewage effluent and agricultural runoff".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] The data gathered through robust volunteer testing is analysed and put into a report helping provide the Environment Agency with information it does not have.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p02] Resources for computer science and scientific crowdsourcing projects concerning COVID-19 can be found on the internet or as apps.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The Citizen Science Global Partnership was created in 2022; the partnership brings together networks from Australia, Africa, Asia, Europe, South America and the USA.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The CitSci Africa Association held its International Conference in February 2024 in Nairobi.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] As technology and public interest grew, the *CitizenScience.Asia* group was set up in 2022; it grew from an initial hackathon in Hong Kong which worked on the 2016 Zika scare.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The network is part of Citizen Science Global Partnership.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The English naturalist Charles Darwin (1809–1882) is widely regarded to have been one of the earliest citizen science contributors in Europe (see § History).
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] A century later, citizen science was experienced by adolescents in Italy during the 1980s, working on urban energy usages and air pollution.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] In his book "Citizen Science", Alan Irwin considers the role that scientific expertise can play in bringing the public and science together and building a more scientifically active citizenry, empowering individuals to contribute to scientific development.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] This includes significant awards such as the EU Citizen Science Project, which is creating a hub for knowledge sharing, coordination, and action.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The European Citizen Science Association (ECSA) was set up in 2014 to encourage the growth of citizen science across Europe, to increase public participation in scientific processes, mainly by initiating and supporting citizen science projects as well as conducting research.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] ECSA has a membership of over 250 individual and organisational members from over 30 countries across the European Union and beyond.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] Examples of citizen science organisations and associations based in Europe include the Biosphere Expeditions (Ireland), Bürger schaffen Wissen (Germany), Scivil (Belgium), Citizen Science Lab at Leiden University (Netherlands), Ibercivis (See External Links), Österreich forscht (Austria).
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] Other organisations can be found here: EU Citizen Science.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The European Citizen Science Association was created in 2014, with some nations also having national bodies, such as Citizen Science Ireland.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] In 2023, the European Union Prize for Citizen Science was established.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] Bestowed through Ars Electronica, the prize was designed to honor, present and support "outstanding projects whose social and political impact advances the further development of a pluralistic, inclusive and sustainable society in Europe".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The first Conference on Public Participation in Scientific Research was held in Portland, Oregon, in August 2012.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] Citizen science is now often a theme at large conferences, such as the annual meeting of the American Geophysical Union.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] In 2010, 2012 and 2014 there were three Citizen Cyberscience summits, organised by the Citizen Cyberscience Centre in Geneva and University College London.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The 2014 summit was hosted in London and attracted over 300 participants.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] In November 2015, the ETH Zürich and University of Zürich hosted an international meeting on the "Challenges and Opportunities in Citizen Science".
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The first citizen science conference hosted by the Citizen Science Association was in San Jose, California, in February 2015 in partnership with the AAAS conference.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The Citizen Science Association conference, CitSci 2017, was held in Saint Paul, Minnesota, United States, between 17 and 20 May 2017.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The conference had more than 600 attendees.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The next CitSci was in March 2019 in Raleigh, North Carolina.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] The platform "Österreich forscht" hosts the annual Austrian citizen science conference since 2015.
[src:anecdata-org/citizen-science-p03] Barbara Kingsolver's 2012 novel *Flight Behaviour* looks at the effects of citizen science on a housewife in Appalachia, when her interest in butterflies brings her into contact with scientists and academics.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The **Cornell Lab of Ornithology** is a member-supported unit of Cornell University in Ithaca, New York, which studies birds and other wildlife.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] It is housed in the Imogene Powers Johnson Center for Birds and Biodiversity in Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Approximately 250 scientists, professors, staff, and students work in a variety of programs devoted to the Lab's mission: interpreting and conserving the Earth's biological diversity through research, education, and citizen science focused on birds.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Work at the Lab is supported primarily by its 200,000 members and supporters.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Cornell Lab produces a quarterly publication, *Living Bird* magazine, and an electronic newsletter delivered twice per month.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] It manages numerous participatory science projects and websites, including the Webby Award-winning *All About Birds*.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Cornell Lab of Ornithology was founded by Arthur A.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Allen, who had lobbied for the creation of the country's first graduate program in ornithology; the Lab was established at Cornell University in 1915.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Initially, the Lab of Ornithology was housed in the university’s entomology and limnology department.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Birder and businessman Lyman Stuart, donors, and landowners purchased or donated farmland in 1954, which was to be set aside for the sanctuary.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Stuart helped finance the construction of the first Lab building in 1957.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] In addition to Allen, others who have been Director (now Louis Agassiz Fuertes Director) of the lab have included Peter Paul Kellogg, Olin Sewall Pettingill Jr.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Cornell Lab of Ornithology is housed in the Imogene Powers Johnson Center for Birds and Biodiversity, which opened in the summer of 2003.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] It is approximately 4 miles from the Cornell University campus.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Previously, it was located within the Lyman K.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Stuart Observatory, near the current Visitor Center.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The 300-acre Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary contains more than 5 miles of trails winding around Sapsucker Pond, on boardwalks, through wetlands and forest.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] More than 230 species of birds have been recorded in the sanctuary.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Approximately 55,000 people visit the sanctuary and public areas of the Cornell Lab each year.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] In fall 2023, the Visitor Center underwent an extensive refurbishment.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] It reopened in June 2024 with new interactive exhibits.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Cornell Lab of Ornithology is a nonprofit organization within Cornell University's College of Agriculture and Life Sciences.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] It has a separate 30-member Administrative Board that is appointed by the Cornell Board of Trustees.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] As of fiscal year 2025, 75% of the lab's revenue, totaling 51.5 million dollars, came from sponsors and members.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] It has 18 senior staff, which includes eight holding Cornell faculty appointments.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Collecting the observations of everyday birders for scientific use is a hallmark of the Lab.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Birdwatchers of all ages and skill levels help gather the data needed to capture the big picture about the distribution and abundance of birds.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Hundreds of thousands of people worldwide participate in the Lab's projects in the Center for Engagement in Science and Nature.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The eBird project allows birders to report any of the Earth's more than 10,585 bird species to a single scientific database.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] As of July 2024, 127.5 million checklists have been recorded, reporting 10,826 species, from more than a million eBirders. eBird data and ground-breaking tools have formed the foundation for hundreds of scientific studies of birds.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Cornell Lab's other participatory-science projects take place in all seasons and include Project FeederWatch, NestWatch, and Celebrate Urban Birds.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Every February, the Lab, the Audubon Society, and Birds Canada host the 4-day Great Backyard Bird Count which takes place all over the world.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Cornell Lab also operates many Bird Cams which stream live video of nesting birds in the spring.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Lab's Bird Academy and curricula take education about birds and nature to students of all ages.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Bird Academy is home to a series of self-paced online courses about woodpeckers, hummingbirds, how to paint birds, photograph birds, improve bird ID skills, and much more.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] K–12 materials are aimed at both students and teachers, assisting them in teaching and learning how to think like a scientist.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Cornell Lab publishes the free Merlin Bird ID app for iOS and Android devices.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] This field guide and identification app guides helps users to put a name to the birds they see, and covers 3,000 species of across the Americas, Western Europe, and India.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] In addition to browsing customized lists of birds for any location in the world, users can answer simple questions to get a list of most likely species, along with images and sound.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] In 2017, Merlin Bird ID was updated to include AI-powered automatic photo recognition, which allows quick identification help with photographs.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Bird ID and Photo ID require separate file downloads.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The app also offers Sound ID, which can identify some 450 North American species, in real time or from an in-app recording, even if multiple species are communicating at once.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The app also displays a basic black-and-white spectrogram—a visual representation of sound.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] To test your knowledge of bird species, the Cornell Lab offers custom quizzing through BirdWise, which tests identification of over 640 species of birds throughout the United States and Canada.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] As of 2025, the Merlin Bird ID app has 10 million users.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Cornell Lab's Project FeederWatch is a database for monitoring bird species.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The information is collected from participants across North America, who count bird species seen at their feeders or in their communities.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] It focuses on populations of bird species in the winter, and scientists at the Cornell Lab take that information to create population maps.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] This information is used to study bird population biology, trends of increasing or decreasing population numbers across the continent, and potential clues for scientists as to why these changes are happening.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Cornell Lab scientists, postdoctoral associates, students, and visiting scholars are carrying on much original research in behavioral ecology, conservation, education, evolutionary biology, information systems, and population genetics.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The scientists even harness weather radar data to study the movements of birds during migration.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Cornell Lab engineers also develop hardware and software tools used in researching bird and animal communication and patterns of movement.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] In the Center for Biodiversity Studies & Higher Education, laboratory researchers are extracting DNA from living birds or specimens to uncover the relationships among species.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] In addition to many studies and published papers, the Cornell Lab's Center for Avian Population Studies has produced land managers' guides aimed at conserving dwindling populations of scarlet tanagers, wood thrushes, and other forest birds.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Lab worked with Partners in Flight to identify rapidly declining species and produce the first North American Landbird Conservation Plan.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Lab staff also worked with multiple partners to create the first-ever State of the Birds report in March 2009, and subsequent years.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Lab scientists are currently involved with partners from industry, government agencies, and non-governmental organizations in setting research priorities to better understand the impact of wind power facilities on birds and bats on land, and on whales and marine creatures offshore.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Lisa Yang Center for Conservation Bioacoustics creates remote recording devices used by researchers in projects around the world.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] These mobile autonomous vehicles consist of a hard drive, housing, and microphone array that can be mounted in a forest or anchored to the ocean floor.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] These recording units have been used in the Yang Center's Elephant Listening Project in Africa, studies of whales, and in many studies of birds such as northern spotted owls.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Yang Center has also developed sound-analysis software programs called Raven and Raven Lite.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Engineers are working on programmable radio tags to track birds and other animals for longer periods of time and to follow bird migrations.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] From its earliest days, the Cornell Lab has had a special interest in bird and animal sounds.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Founder Arthur Allen and his students were pioneers in the field, recording the first bird songs on a film soundtrack.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Macaulay Library has since expanded and is now the world's premier scientific archive of natural history audio, video, and photographs.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The library hosts over 64 million audio, video and photographs.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Macaulay Library archivists continue to mount expeditions to collect wildlife sounds, images, and video from around the world and collect media from contributors to expand the archive.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Lab's Center for Conservation Media presents stories from around the world, working with many partners to highlight conservation concerns ranging from the preservation of important habitats to individual species in trouble such as the great Philippine eagle and the African grey parrot.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] The Cornell University Museum of Vertebrates is also housed in the Johnson Center and holds 1,230,000 specimens of fish, 44,300 amphibians and reptiles, 45,000 birds, 3,200 eggs, and 15,000 mammals, some now extinct.
[src:anecdata-org/cornell-lab-of-ornithology] Students and scientists use the collections in their studies.
